AdaRank: A Boosting Algorithm for Information Retrieval 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:In this paper we address the issue of learning to rank for document retrieval .
1-2:In the task, a model is automatically created with some training data and then is utilized for ranking of documents .
1-3:The goodness of a model is usually evaluated with performance measures such as MAP (Mean Average Precision) and NDCG (Normalized Discounted Cumulative Gain) .
1-4:Ideally a learning algorithm would train a ranking model that could directly optimize the performance measures with respect to the training data .
1-5:Existing methods, however, are only able to train ranking models by minimizing loss functions loosely related to the performance measures .
1-6:For example, Ranking SVM and RankBoost train ranking models by minimizing classification errors on instance pairs .
1-7:To deal with the problem, we propose a novel learning algorithm within the framework of boosting, which can minimize a loss function directly defined on the performance measures .
1-8:Our algorithm, referred to as AdaRank, repeatedly constructs ‘weak rankers" on the basis of re weighted training data and finally linearly combines the weak rankers for making ranking predictions .
1-9:We prove that the training process of AdaRank is exactly that of enhancing the performance measure used .
1-10:Experimental results on four benchmark datasets show that AdaRank significantly outperforms the baseline methods of BM25, Ranking SVM, and RankBoost .
1-11:H.3.3 [Information Search and Retrieval]: Retrieval models .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:Recently ‘learning to rank" has gained increasing attention in both the fields of information retrieval and machine learning .
2-2:When applied to document retrieval, learning to rank becomes a task as follows .
2-3:In training, a ranking model is constructed with data consisting of queries, their corresponding retrieved documents, and relevance levels given by humans .
2-4:In ranking, given a new query, the corresponding retrieved documents are sorted by using the trained ranking model .
2-5:In document retrieval, usually ranking results are evaluated in terms of performance measures such as MAP (Mean Average Precision) [1] and NDCG (Normalized Discounted Cumulative Gain) [15] .
2-6:Ideally, the ranking function is created so that the accuracy of ranking in terms of one of the measures with respect to the training data is maximized .
2-7:Several methods for learning to rank have been developed and applied to document retrieval .
2-8:For example, Herbrich et al .
2-9:[13] propose a learning algorithm for ranking on the basis of Support Vector Machines, called Ranking SVM .
2-10:Freund et al .
2-11:[8] take a similar approach and perform the learning by using boosting, referred to as RankBoost .
2-12:All the existing methods used for document retrieval [2, 3, 8, 13, 16, 20] are designed to optimize loss functions loosely related to the IR performance measures, not loss functions directly based on the measures .
2-13:For example, Ranking SVM and RankBoost train ranking models by minimizing classification errors on instance pairs .
2-14:In this paper, we aim to develop a new learning algorithm that can directly optimize any performance measure used in document retrieval .
2-15:Inspired by the work of AdaBoost for classification [9], we propose to develop a boosting algorithm for information retrieval, referred to as AdaRank .
2-16:AdaRank utilizes a linear combination of ‘weak rankers" as its model .
2-17:In learning, it repeats the process of re weighting the training sample, creating a weak ranker, and calculating a weight for the ranker .
2-18:We show that AdaRank algorithm can iteratively optimize an exponential loss function based on any of IR performance measures .
2-19:A lower bound of the performance on training data is given, which indicates that the ranking accuracy in terms of the performance measure can be continuously improved during the training process .
2-20:AdaRank offers several advantages: ease in implementation, theoretical soundness, efficiency in training, and high accuracy in ranking .
2-21:Experimental results indicate that AdaRank can outperform the baseline methods of BM25, Ranking SVM, and RankBoost, on four benchmark datasets including OHSUMED, WSJ, AP, and .Gov .
2-22:Tuning ranking models using certain training data and a performance measure is a common practice in IR [1] .
2-23:As the number of features in the ranking model gets larger and the amount of training data gets larger, the tuning becomes harder .
2-24:From the viewpoint of IR, AdaRank can be viewed as a machine learning method for ranking model tuning .
2-25:Recently, direct optimization of performance measures in learning has become a hot research topic .
2-26:Several methods for classification [17] and ranking [5, 19] have been proposed .
2-27:AdaRank can be viewed as a machine learning method for direct optimization of performance measures, based on a different approach .
2-28:The rest of the paper is organized as follows .
2-29:After a summary of related work in Section 2, we describe the proposed AdaRank algorithm in details in Section 3 .
2-30:Experimental results and discussions are given in Section 4 .
2-31:Section 5 concludes this paper and gives future work. .
3 RELATED WORK :
3-1:2.1 Information Retrieval The key problem for document retrieval is ranking, specifically, how to create the ranking model (function) that can sort documents based on their relevance to the given query .
3-2:It is a common practice in IR to tune the parameters of a ranking model using some labeled data and one performance measure [1] .
3-3:For example, the state ofthe art methods of BM25 [24] and LMIR (Language Models for Information Retrieval) [18, 22] all have parameters to tune .
3-4:As the ranking models become more sophisticated (more features are used) and more labeled data become available, how to tune or train ranking models turns out to be a challenging issue .
3-5:Recently methods of ‘learning to rank" have been applied to ranking model construction and some promising results have been obtained .
3-6:For example, Joachims [16] applies Ranking SVM to document retrieval .
3-7:He utilizes click through data to deduce training data for the model creation .
3-8:Cao et al .
3-9:[4] adapt Ranking SVM to document retrieval by modifying the Hinge Loss function to better meet the requirements of IR .
3-10:Specifically, they introduce a Hinge Loss function that heavily penalizes errors on the tops of ranking lists and errors from queries with fewer retrieved documents .
3-11:Burges et al .
3-12:[3] employ Relative Entropy as a loss function and Gradient Descent as an algorithm to train a Neural Network model for ranking in document retrieval .
3-13:The method is referred to as ‘RankNet" .
3-14:2.2 Machine Learning There are three topics in machine learning which are related to our current work .
3-15:They are ‘learning to rank", boosting, and direct optimization of performance measures .
3-16:Learning to rank is to automatically create a ranking function that assigns scores to instances and then rank the instances by using the scores .
3-17:Several approaches have been proposed to tackle the problem .
3-18:One major approach to learning to rank is that of transforming it into binary classification on instance pairs .
3-19:This ‘pair wise" approach fits well with information retrieval and thus is widely used in IR .
3-20:Typical methods of the approach include Ranking SVM [13], RankBoost [8], and RankNet [3] .
3-21:For other approaches to learning to rank, refer to [2, 11, 31] .
3-22:In the pair wise approach to ranking, the learning task is formalized as a problem of classifying instance pairs into two categories (correctly ranked and incorrectly ranked) .
3-23:Actually, it is known that reducing classification errors on instance pairs is equivalent to maximizing a lower bound of MAP [16] .
3-24:In that sense, the existing methods of Ranking SVM, RankBoost, and RankNet are only able to minimize loss functions that are loosely related to the IR performance measures .
3-25:Boosting is a general technique for improving the accuracies of machine learning algorithms .
3-26:The basic idea of boosting is to repeatedly construct ‘weak learners" by re weighting training data and form an ensemble of weak learners such that the total performance of the ensemble is ‘boosted" .
3-27:Freund and Schapire have proposed the first well known boosting algorithm called AdaBoost (Adaptive Boosting) [9], which is designed for binary classification (0 1 prediction) .
3-28:Later, Schapire & Singer have introduced a generalized version of AdaBoost in which weak learners can give confidence scores in their predictions rather than make 0 1 decisions [26] .
3-29:Extensions have been made to deal with the problems of multi class classification [10, 26], regression [7], and ranking [8] .
3-30:In fact, AdaBoost is an algorithm that ingeniously constructs a linear model by minimizing the ‘exponential loss function" with respect to the training data [26] .
3-31:Our work in this paper can be viewed as a boosting method developed for ranking, particularly for ranking in IR .
3-32:Recently, a number of authors have proposed conducting direct optimization of multivariate performance measures in learning .
3-33:For instance, Joachims [17] presents an SVM method to directly optimize nonlinear multivariate performance measures like the F1 measure for classification .
3-34:Cossock & Zhang [5] find a way to approximately optimize the ranking performance measure DCG [15] .
3-35:Metzler et al .
3-36:[19] also propose a method of directly maximizing rank based metrics for ranking on the basis of manifold learning .
3-37:AdaRank is also one that tries to directly optimize multivariate performance measures, but is based on a different approach .
3-38:AdaRank is unique in that it employs an exponential loss function based on IR performance measures and a boosting technique. .
4 OUR METHOD: ADARANK :
4-1:3.1 General Framework We first describe the general framework of learning to rank for document retrieval .
4-2:In retrieval (testing), given a query the system returns a ranking list of documents in descending order of the relevance scores .
4-3:The relevance scores are calculated with a ranking function (model) .
4-4:In learning (training), a number of queries and their corresponding retrieved documents are given .
4-5:Furthermore, the relevance levels of the documents with respect to the queries are also provided .
4-6:The relevance levels are represented as ranks (i.e., categories in a total order) .
4-7:The objective of learning is to construct a ranking function which achieves the best results in ranking of the training data in the sense of minimization of a loss function .
4-8:Ideally the loss function is defined on the basis of the performance measure used in testing .
4-9:Suppose that Y = {r1, r2, · · · , r } is a set of ranks, where denotes the number of ranks .
4-10:There exists a total order between the ranks r r −1 · · · r1, where ‘ " denotes a preference relationship .
4-11:In training, a set of queries Q = {q1, q2, · · · , qm} is given .
4-12:Each query qi is associated with a list of retrieved documents di = {di1, di2, · · · , di,n(qi)} and a list of labels yi = {yi1, yi2, · · · , yi,n(qi)}, where n(qi) denotes the sizes of lists di and yi, dij denotes the jth document in di, and yij ∈ Y denotes the rank of document di j .
4-13:A feature vector xij = Ψ(qi, di j) ∈ X is created from each query document pair (qi, di j), i = 1, 2, · · · , m; j = 1, 2, · · · , n(qi) .
4-14:Thus, the training set can be represented as S = {(qi, di, yi)}m i=1 .
4-15:The objective of learning is to create a ranking function f : X → , such that for each query the elements in its corresponding document list can be assigned relevance scores using the function and then be ranked according to the scores .
4-16:Specifically, we create a permutation of integers π(qi, di, f) for query qi, the corresponding list of documents di, and the ranking function f .
4-17:Let di = {di1, di2, · · · , di,n(qi)} be identified by the list of integers {1, 2, · · · , n(qi)}, then permutation π(qi, di, f) is defined as a bijection from {1, 2, · · · , n(qi)} to itself .
4-18:We use π( j) to denote the position of item j (i.e., di j) .
4-19:The learning process turns out to be that of minimizing the loss function which represents the disagreement between the permutation π(qi, di, f) and the list of ranks yi, for all of the queries .
