4-35:3.2 Algorithm Inspired by the AdaBoost algorithm for classification, we have devised a novel algorithm which can optimize a loss function based on the IR performance measures .
4-36:The algorithm is referred to as ‘AdaRank" and is shown in Figure 1 .
4-37:AdaRank takes a training set S = {(qi, di, yi)}m i=1 as input and takes the performance measure function E and the number of iterations T as parameters .
4-38:AdaRank runs T rounds and at each round it creates a weak ranker ht(t = 1, · · · , T) .
4-39:Finally, it outputs a ranking model f by linearly combining the weak rankers .
4-40:At each round, AdaRank maintains a distribution of weights over the queries in the training data .
4-41:We denote the distribution of weights Input: S = {(qi, di, yi)}m i=1, and parameters E and T Initialize P1(i) = 1 m .
4-42:For t = 1, · · · , T • Create weak ranker ht with weighted distribution Pt on training data S .
4-43:• Choose αt αt = 1 2 · ln m i=1 Pt(i){1 + E(π(qi, di, ht), yi)} m i=1 Pt(i){1 − E(π(qi, di, ht), yi)} .
4-44:• Create ft ft(x) = t k=1 αkhk(x) .
4-45:• Update Pt+1 Pt+1(i) = exp{−E(π(qi, di, ft), yi)} m j=1 exp{−E(π(qj, dj, ft), yj)} .
4-46:End For Output ranking model: f(x) = fT (x) .
4-47:Figure 1: The AdaRank algorithm .
4-48:at round t as Pt and the weight on the ith training query qi at round t as Pt(i) .
4-49:Initially, AdaRank sets equal weights to the queries .
4-50:At each round, it increases the weights of those queries that are not ranked well by ft, the model created so far .
4-51:As a result, the learning at the next round will be focused on the creation of a weak ranker that can work on the ranking of those ‘hard" queries .
4-52:At each round, a weak ranker ht is constructed based on training data with weight distribution Pt .
4-53:The goodness of a weak ranker is measured by the performance measure E weighted by Pt: m i=1 Pt(i)E(π(qi, di, ht), yi) .
4-54:Several methods for weak ranker construction can be considered .
4-55:For example, a weak ranker can be created by using a subset of queries (together with their document list and label list) sampled according to the distribution Pt .
4-56:In this paper, we use single features as weak rankers, as will be explained in Section 3.6 .
4-57:Once a weak ranker ht is built, AdaRank chooses a weight αt > 0 for the weak ranker .
4-58:Intuitively, αt measures the importance of ht .
4-59:A ranking model ft is created at each round by linearly combining the weak rankers constructed so far h1, · · · , ht with weights α1, · · · , αt .
4-60:ft is then used for updating the distribution Pt+1 .
4-61:3.3 Theoretical Analysis The existing learning algorithms for ranking attempt to minimize a loss function based on instance pairs (document pairs) .
4-62:In contrast, AdaRank tries to optimize a loss function based on queries .
4-63:Furthermore, the loss function in AdaRank is defined on the basis of general IR performance measures .
4-64:The measures can be MAP, NDCG, WTA, MRR, or any other measures whose range is within [−1, +1] .
4-65:We next explain why this is the case .
4-66:Ideally we want to maximize the ranking accuracy in terms of a performance measure on the training data: max f∈F m i=1 E(π(qi, di, f), yi), (4) where F is the set of possible ranking functions .
4-67:This is equivalent to minimizing the loss on the training data min f∈F m i=1 (1 − E(π(qi, di, f), yi)) .
4-68:(5) It is difficult to directly optimize the loss, because E is a noncontinuous function and thus may be difficult to handle .
4-69:We instead attempt to minimize an upper bound of the loss in (5) min f∈F m i=1 exp{−E(π(qi, di, f), yi)}, (6) because e−x ≥ 1 − x holds for any x ∈ .
4-70:We consider the use of a linear combination of weak rankers as our ranking model: f(x) = T t=1 αtht(x) .
4-71:(7) The minimization in (6) then turns out to be min ht∈H,αt∈ + L(ht, αt) = m i=1 exp{−E(π(qi, di, ft−1 + αtht), yi)}, (8) where H is the set of possible weak rankers, αt is a positive weight, and ( ft−1 + αtht)(x) = ft−1(x) + αtht(x) .
4-72:Several ways of computing coefficients αt and weak rankers ht may be considered .
4-73:Following the idea of AdaBoost, in AdaRank we take the approach of ‘forward stage wise additive modeling" [12] and get the algorithm in Figure accuracy for AdaRank on training data, as presented in Theorem 1 .
