4-75:The following bound holds on the ranking accuracy of the AdaRank algorithm on training data: 1 m m i=1 E(π(qi, di, fT ), yi) ≥ 1 − T t=1 e−δt min 1 − ϕ(t)2, where ϕ(t) = m i=1 Pt(i)E(π(qi, di, ht), yi), δt min = mini=1,··· ,m δt i, and δt i = E(π(qi, di, ft−1 + αtht), yi) − E(π(qi, di, ft−1), yi) −αtE(π(qi, di, ht), yi), for all i = 1, 2, · · · , m and t = 1, 2, · · · , T .
4-76:A proof of the theorem can be found in appendix .
4-77:The theorem implies that the ranking accuracy in terms of the performance measure can be continuously improved, as long as e−δt min 1 − ϕ(t)2 < 1 holds .
4-78:3.4 Advantages AdaRank is a simple yet powerful method .
4-79:More importantly, it is a method that can be justified from the theoretical viewpoint, as discussed above .
4-80:In addition AdaRank has several other advantages when compared with the existing learning to rank methods such as Ranking SVM, RankBoost, and RankNet .
4-81:First, AdaRank can incorporate any performance measure, provided that the measure is query based and in the range of [−1, +1] .
4-82:Notice that the major IR measures meet this requirement .
4-83:In contrast the existing methods only minimize loss functions that are loosely related to the IR measures [16] .
4-84:Second, the learning process of AdaRank is more efficient than those of the existing learning algorithms .
4-85:The time complexity of AdaRank is of order O((k+T)·m·n log n), where k denotes the number of features, T the number of rounds, m the number of queries in training data, and n is the maximum number of documents for queries in training data .
4-86:The time complexity of RankBoost, for example, is of order O(T · m · n2 ) [8] .
4-87:Third, AdaRank employs a more reasonable framework for performing the ranking task than the existing methods .
4-88:Specifically in AdaRank the instances correspond to queries, while in the existing methods the instances correspond to document pairs .
4-89:As a result, AdaRank does not have the following shortcomings that plague the existing methods .
4-90:(a) The existing methods have to make a strong assumption that the document pairs from the same query are independently distributed .
4-91:In reality, this is clearly not the case and this problem does not exist for AdaRank .
4-92:(b) Ranking the most relevant documents on the tops of document lists is crucial for document retrieval .
4-93:The existing methods cannot focus on the training on the tops, as indicated in [4] .
4-94:Several methods for rectifying the problem have been proposed (e.g., [4]), however, they do not seem to fundamentally solve the problem .
4-95:In contrast, AdaRank can naturally focus on training on the tops of document lists, because the performance measures used favor rankings for which relevant documents are on the tops .
4-96:(c) In the existing methods, the numbers of document pairs vary from query to query, resulting in creating models biased toward queries with more document pairs, as pointed out in [4] .
4-97:AdaRank does not have this drawback, because it treats queries rather than document pairs as basic units in learning .
4-98:3.5 Differences from AdaBoost AdaRank is a boosting algorithm .
4-99:In that sense, it is similar to AdaBoost, but it also has several striking differences from AdaBoost .
4-100:First, the types of instances are different .
4-101:AdaRank makes use of queries and their corresponding document lists as instances .
4-102:The labels in training data are lists of ranks (relevance levels) .
4-103:AdaBoost makes use of feature vectors as instances .
4-104:The labels in training data are simply +1 and −1 .
4-105:Second, the performance measures are different .
4-106:In AdaRank, the performance measure is a generic measure, defined on the document list and the rank list of a query .
4-107:In AdaBoost the corresponding performance measure is a specific measure for binary classification, also referred to as ‘margin" [25] .
4-108:Third, the ways of updating weights are also different .
4-109:In AdaBoost, the distribution of weights on training instances is calculated according to the current distribution and the performance of the current weak learner .
4-110:In AdaRank, in contrast, it is calculated according to the performance of the ranking model created so far, as shown in Figure 1 .
4-111:Note that AdaBoost can also adopt the weight updating method used in AdaRank .
4-112:For AdaBoost they are equivalent (cf., [12] page 305) .
4-113:However, this is not true for AdaRank .
4-114:3.6 Construction of Weak Ranker We consider an efficient implementation for weak ranker construction, which is also used in our experiments .
4-115:In the implementation, as weak ranker we choose the feature that has the optimal weighted performance among all of the features: max k m i=1 Pt(i)E(π(qi, di, xk), yi) .
4-116:Creating weak rankers in this way, the learning process turns out to be that of repeatedly selecting features and linearly combining the selected features .
4-117:Note that features which are not selected in the training phase will have a weight of zero. .
