5-5:4.1 Experiment Setting Ranking SVM [13, 16] and RankBoost [8] were selected as baselines in the experiments, because they are the state of the art learning to rank methods .
5-6:Furthermore, BM25 [24] was used as a baseline, representing the state of the arts IR method (we actually used the tool Lemur1 ) .
5-7:For AdaRank, the parameter T was determined automatically during each experiment .
5-8:Specifically, when there is no improvement in ranking accuracy in terms of the performance measure, the iteration stops (and T is determined) .
5-9:As the measure E, MAP and NDCG@5 were utilized .
5-10:The results for AdaRank using MAP and NDCG@5 as measures in training are represented as AdaRank.MAP and AdaRank.NDCG, respectively .
5-11:4.2 Experiment with OHSUMED Data In this experiment, we made use of the OHSUMED dataset [14] to test the performances of AdaRank .
5-12:The OHSUMED dataset consists of 348,566 documents and 106 queries .
5-13:There are in total 16,140 query document pairs upon which relevance judgments are made .
5-14:The relevance judgments are either ‘d" (definitely relevant), ‘p" (possibly relevant), or ‘n"(not relevant) .
5-15:The data have been used in many experiments in IR, for example [4, 29] .
5-16:As features, we adopted those used in document retrieval [4] .
5-17:Table 2 shows the features .
5-18:For example, tf (term frequency), idf (inverse document frequency), dl (document length), and combinations of them are defined as features .
5-19:BM25 score itself is also a feature .
5-20:Stop words were removed and stemming was conducted in the data .
5-21:We randomly divided queries into four even subsets and conducted 4 fold cross validation experiments .
5-22:We tuned the parameters for BM25 during one of the trials and applied them to the other trials .
5-23:The results reported in Figure 2 are those averaged over four trials .
