5-27:From Figure 2, we see that both AdaRank.MAP and AdaRank.NDCG outperform BM25, Ranking SVM, and RankBoost in terms of all measures .
5-28:We conducted significant tests (t test) on the improvements of AdaRank.MAP over BM25, Ranking SVM, and RankBoost in terms of MAP .
5-29:The results indicate that all the improvements are statistically significant (p value < 0.05) .
5-30:We also conducted t test on the improvements of AdaRank.NDCG over BM25, Ranking SVM, and RankBoost in terms of NDCG@5 .
5-31:The improvements are also statistically significant .
5-32:4.3 Experiment with WSJ and AP Data In this experiment, we made use of the WSJ and AP datasets from the TREC ad hoc retrieval track, to test the performances of AdaRank .
5-33:WSJ contains 74,520 articles of Wall Street Journals from 1990 to 1992, and AP contains 158,240 articles of Associated Press in 1988 and 1990 .
5-34:200 queries are selected from the TREC topics (No.101 ∼ No.300) .
5-35:Each query has a number of documents associated and they are labeled as ‘relevant" or ‘irrelevant" (to the query) .
5-36:Following the practice in [28], the queries that have less than 10 relevant documents were discarded .
5-37:Table 3 shows the statistics on the two datasets .
5-38:In the same way as in section 4.2, we adopted the features listed in Table 2 for ranking .
